The XPK package. Preferably som more (and newer) xpk-libraries.
Kickstart 3.0 (At least you have to have arexx and the cli-commands I use).
A running rexx-server.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Configuration"
@prev "Requirements"

Copy the files wherever you'd like them. (i.e. in "REXX:")
@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Configuration"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Installation"

Click the CreateConfig.rexx icon :)

You might also want to load the configfile in an editor, and put a ";" in
front of all libraries you don't want to test. The configfile will be put in
"S:".
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "History-todo"
@prev "Configuration"

Template: FILENAME/S,LIB/K

"/S" = The option is a switch. Enter the name of the option to specify that
       option.
"/K" = Always use the option's keyword before the argument if the argument
       is given.

Examples:

"RX xpkTEST.rexx ram:#? lib SQSH" - Will test all files in the Ram Disk
                                    (excluding files in subdirectories) with
                                    xpkSQSH.library.
"RX xpkTEST.rexx" - Will bring up a filerequester. The file(s) you select
                    will be tested with all valid libraries mentioned in the
                    configfile.

NB!  * Arguments can be put in any order you'd like.
     * Giving a filename with spaces in it (i.e. "Bourbon Street") won't
       work. You can, however, also test these files by using wildcards (i.e.
       "Bourbon?Street" or "#?").
     * This script will not work with libraries which needs a password (for
       encryption). Such libraries are i.e. DLTA, FEAL, IDEA and ENCO.
     * I've experienced that the xpkRDCN library is lossy. So make sure you
       do a backup if you want to test this one!
     * All usage is at your own risk. I take no responsibilities.
@endnode

@node "History-todo" "History/todo"
@next "Feedback"
